  <p>
    Let <m>f(x)=$f</m>.
    Answer the following questions.
  </p>

  <p>
    1. Find the largest \emph{open} interval(s) on which
    <m>f</m> is increasing. If there is more than one interval,
    write your answer as a union of the intervals.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answer (in interval notation):
    <answer><award>$ans1</award></answer>
  </p>

  <p>
    2. Find the largest \emph{open} interval(s) on which
    <m>f</m> is decreasing. If there is more than one interval,
    write your answer as a union of the intervals.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answer (in interval notation):
    <answer><award>$ans2</award></answer>
  </p>

  <p>
    3. Find the local maxima of <m>f</m>.
    \textbf{List your answers as points in the form}
    <m>(a,b)</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answer (separate by commas):
    <answer><award symbolicEquality>$ans3</award></answer>
  </p>

  <p>
    4. Find the local minima of <m>f</m>.
    \textbf{List your answers as points in the form}
    <m>(a,b)</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answer (separate by commas):
    <answer><award>$ans4</award></answer>
  </p>

  <p>
    5. Find the largest \emph{open} interval(s) on
    which <m>f</m> is concave upward. If there is
    more than one interval, write your answer as a
    union of the intervals.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answer (in interval notation):
    <answer><award>$ans5</award></answer>
  </p>

  <p>
    6. Find the largest \emph{open} interval(s) on
    which <m>f</m> is concave downward. If there is
    more than one interval, write your answer as a
    union of the intervals.
  </p>
  <p>
    Answer (in interval notation):
    <answer><award>$ans6</award></answer>
  </p>

